First, I need to consider edge cases. If the number is less than 2, it cannot be prime, so the algorithm should immediately return `false`. For numbers greater than or equal to 2, I’ll need to check divisibility. Instead of checking all numbers up to `num - 1`, I can optimize by only checking up to the square root of `num`. This is because if `num` has a factor greater than its square root, the corresponding factor must be less than the square root, so checking up to the square root is sufficient.

I’ll initialize a variable `isPrime` to `true` to assume the number is prime initially. Then, I’ll loop through integers from 2 to the square root of `num`. If `num` is divisible by any of these integers, I’ll set `isPrime` to `false` and break out of the loop. Finally, I’ll return the value of `isPrime`.

